    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">02</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Definition</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">What Does 'Texican' Mean?</h2><ul><li>'Texican' refers to early inhabitants of Texas with mixed Spanish, Mexican, and Anglo heritage</li><li>The term highlights cultural blending unique to Texas frontier life</li><li>It predates the modern term 'Texan' and carries historical significance</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican identifies a group of people living in Texas during the early 19th century who embodied a hybrid cultural identity shaped by Spanish colonial roots and Mexican governance, alongside Anglo-American influences. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texicans often spoke Spanish and English, practiced Catholicism, and lived in frontier settlements blending Mexican and Anglo customs.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> List cultural elements you think might characterize Texican identity based on this definition.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Do not conflate 'Texican' with 'Texan' as used today; the former has a specific historical and cultural meaning.</p></div></div>",
