    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">03</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Etymology</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Origins of the Word 'Texas'</h2><ul><li>'Texas' derives from the Caddo word 'tejas' meaning 'friends' or 'allies'</li><li>Spanish explorers adopted and adapted the term in the 17th century</li><li>The name reflects early indigenous and colonial interactions</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The name 'Texas' originates from the Caddo language, signifying friendship or alliance, which Spanish colonists adopted, illustrating early cultural contact and exchange. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Spanish explorers used 'Tejas' to refer to friendly indigenous groups, which later became the name of the region and state.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Consider how place names can reflect historical relationships between peoples.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Avoid assuming 'Texas' is a Spanish word; it is a transliteration of an indigenous term.</p></div></div>",
