    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">04</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Etymology</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Exploring 'Texican': A Linguistic Blend</h2><ul><li>'Texican' combines 'Texas' with the suffix '-ican' indicating belonging or origin</li><li>Reflects a hybrid identity linking geography and culture</li><li>Used historically to describe residents with mixed heritage</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The term 'Texican' linguistically merges the place name 'Texas' with a suffix denoting identity, emphasizing the connection between land and cultural belonging. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Similar to 'Mexican' or 'American,' 'Texican' signals a person from Texas with a distinct cultural identity.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Think of other identity terms formed by combining place names and suffixes.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Do not overlook the cultural implications embedded in the term's formation.</p></div></div>",
