    "num": "05",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">05</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Historical Context</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Early 19th Century Texas: A Cultural Crossroads</h2><ul><li>Texas was part of Spanish, then Mexican territory before U.S. annexation</li><li>Populated by indigenous peoples, Spanish settlers, Mexicans, and Anglo immigrants</li><li>Texicans emerged as a distinct group amid these cultural interactions</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The early 1800s in Texas were marked by shifting political control and diverse populations, creating a dynamic environment where Texican identity developed. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texicans lived in frontier settlements where Spanish, Mexican, and Anglo customs blended in daily life.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify factors that might influence cultural blending in frontier regions.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Avoid viewing Texas history as solely Anglo-American or Mexican; it was a multicultural frontier.</p></div></div>",
