      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Historical interpretations of Texicans vary, reflecting different emphases on cultural, political, and ethnic factors influencing identity formation.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; facebook.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Scholars debate the precise definition and boundaries of 'Texican' identity</li><li>Some emphasize Spanish colonial roots, others highlight Mexican nationalism</li><li>Anglo-American narratives often overshadow Texican contributions</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Jinx Schwartz's research highlights the frontier family experience, while other sources focus on political loyalties during the Texas Revolution.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Consider why historians might disagree on defining Texican identity.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Avoid accepting a single narrative without considering multiple scholarly perspectives.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; facebook.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p>"
