    "id": "slide14",
    "eyebrow": "Mexican Identity",
    "num": "14",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">14</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Mexican Identity</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texicans and Mexican National Identity</h2><ul><li>Texicans identified as Mexican citizens after 1821 independence</li><li>Mexican laws and customs influenced Texican governance and society</li><li>Tensions arose between Texican local customs and central Mexican policies</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Following Mexico's independence from Spain, Texicans became Mexican citizens, adopting Mexican national identity while maintaining local traditions. This dual identity created cultural complexity and occasional conflict with central authorities. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican settlers often followed Mexican land grant policies but resisted central government attempts to impose stricter controls.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Discuss how Texicans balanced Mexican national identity with local cultural practices.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Viewing Texicans as fully assimilated Mexicans without recognizing local distinctiveness and resistance.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 14",
      "h": "Negotiating Mexican Identity in Texas",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Following Mexico's independence from Spain, Texicans became Mexican citizens, adopting Mexican national identity while maintaining local traditions. This dual identity created cultural complexity and occasional conflict with central authorities.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; facebook.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans identified as Mexican citizens after 1821 independence</li><li>Mexican laws and customs influenced Texican governance and society</li><li>Tensions arose between Texican local customs and central Mexican policies</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texican settlers often followed Mexican land grant policies but resisted central government attempts to impose stricter controls.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Discuss how Texicans balanced Mexican national identity with local cultural practices.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Viewing Texicans as fully assimilated Mexicans without recognizing local distinctiveness and resistance.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; facebook.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p>"
    },
