    "id": "slide15",
    "eyebrow": "Family and Frontier Life",
    "num": "15",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">15</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Family and Frontier Life</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Family Structures and Frontier Experience</h2><ul><li>Texican families were often large and multigenerational</li><li>Frontier life demanded self-reliance and community cooperation</li><li>Family roles blended Spanish traditions with frontier adaptations</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican family life combined traditional Spanish colonial structures with adaptations to the challenges of frontier living. Large families supported agricultural work and defense, fostering tight-knit communities. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Families shared labor in ranching and farming, while also organizing communal defense against threats.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Explain how frontier conditions influenced Texican family roles and community ties.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming frontier life diminished traditional family roles rather than transforming them.</p></div></div>",
