      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican family life combined traditional Spanish colonial structures with adaptations to the challenges of frontier living. Large families supported agricultural work and defense, fostering tight-knit communities.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; facebook.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texican families were often large and multigenerational</li><li>Frontier life demanded self-reliance and community cooperation</li><li>Family roles blended Spanish traditions with frontier adaptations</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Families shared labor in ranching and farming, while also organizing communal defense against threats.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Explain how frontier conditions influenced Texican family roles and community ties.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming frontier life diminished traditional family roles rather than transforming them.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; facebook.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p>"
