    "eyebrow": "Settlement Geography",
    "num": "25",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">25</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Settlement Geography</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Settlement Patterns in Early Texas</h2><ul><li>Texicans primarily settled along rivers and fertile plains</li><li>Settlements clustered near water sources for agriculture and transport</li><li>Geographic distribution influenced by Spanish land grant policies</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican communities in early Texas were strategically located near rivers and fertile land to support farming and trade. Spanish colonial land grants shaped where families established homesteads, often forming linear settlements along waterways. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> The San Antonio River area became a hub for Texican settlements due to its reliable water and arable land, fostering community growth.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Map the major rivers in early Texas and identify why Texicans might have chosen these locations for settlement.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texican settlements were randomly dispersed rather than strategically located based on environmental factors.</p></div></div>",
