    "id": "slide34",
    "eyebrow": "Environmental Adaptation",
    "num": "34",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">34</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Environmental Adaptation</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">How Texicans Modified Their Environment</h2><ul><li>Constructed irrigation systems to manage water supply</li><li>Cleared land for agriculture and grazing</li><li>Built homes and community structures suited to climate</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texicans actively modified their environment to support agriculture and settlement sustainability, demonstrating adaptive ingenuity in a challenging frontier landscape. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Irrigation ditches diverted river water to fields, increasing crop yields during dry periods.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify environmental modifications Texicans made and discuss their importance for survival.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming settlers were passive recipients of environmental conditions rather than active modifiers.</p></div></div>",
