    "num": "49",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">49</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Key Primary Source Collections on the Texicans</h2><ul><li>Texas A&amp;M University-San Antonio's digital archives (s9)</li><li>Texas Studies Project's curated primary source sets (s10)</li><li>Lone Star College's Texas history primary sources guide (s11)</li><li>Texas Archive of the Moving Image educational resources (s12)</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">These collections provide authentic documents, letters, maps, and artifacts that illuminate Texican history. They are essential for direct engagement with historical evidence. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Examining a land grant document from s10 reveals how Texicans acquired and managed frontier lands.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Explore one primary source from s10 or s11 and identify what it reveals about Texican life.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming all primary sources are equally reliable without considering context or provenance.</p></div></div>",
