    "eyebrow": "Primary Source Analysis",
    "num": "50",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">50</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Source Analysis</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Critical Interpretation of Texican Documents</h2><ul><li>Assess source origin, purpose, and audience</li><li>Identify language reflecting political or cultural bias</li><li>Cross-check facts with other primary and secondary sources</li><li>Consider historical context and events at time of creation</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Interpreting Texican primary sources requires understanding their context and potential biases to avoid misleading conclusions. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A letter from a Texican soldier (s13) uses patriotic language reflecting pro-independence sentiment, which must be balanced with Mexican government records.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze a Texican letter or official document and note any language or details that suggest bias or perspective.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Taking source content at face value without questioning underlying motives or context.</p></div></div>",
